# Working with tickets in this repo (Ticket-Flow)

This repo uses **Ticket-Flow** — a five-phase, ticket-driven workflow backed by **{{backend.displayName}}**, available in {{#each tools}}{{#unless @first}}, {{/unless}}**{{this}}**{{/each}}. You drive it by talking to your AI assistant in normal language; slash commands are an optional shortcut.

```
next-ticket → describe-ticket → execute-ticket → review-ticket → merge-ticket
                                                     ▲                  │
                                                     └──── fix-ticket ◀─┘
                                            (loops back on PR feedback / red CI)
```

## What each phase does

| Phase | What it does |
|---|---|
| **next-ticket** | Surfaces the next priority backlog tickets (grouped by {{backend.groupingNoun}}) and recommends one to pick up. |
| **describe-ticket** | Turns a ticket into user stories + acceptance criteria + a **test-driven** execution plan, records it on the ticket, and cuts the branch. |
| **execute-ticket** | Builds the plan test-first, then ships it: test gate → push → PR → move to **{{state "inReview"}}**. |
| **review-ticket** | Reviews the PR at a depth you choose, checks it delivers every acceptance criterion, and logs the full review on the ticket. |
| **fix-ticket** | Triages a PR's review comments + failing CI, confirms the scope and a plan with you, then fixes and updates the PR. |
| **merge-ticket** | Gates on the review, merges, closes the ticket, cleans up branches, and surfaces the next priority. |

## How to use it

Just say what you want — the matching phase runs (no slash command needed):

| You say… | Phase |
|---|---|
| "what should I work on next?" | next-ticket |
| "plan {{eg.prefixUpper}}-123" / "break this ticket down" | describe-ticket |
| "build it and open a PR" / "ship it" | execute-ticket |
| "review the PR" / "is it ready?" | review-ticket |
| "fix the review comments" / "fix the failing CI" | fix-ticket |
| "merge it" / "close out the ticket" | merge-ticket |

Prefer explicit control? Invoke a phase directly: {{skillRef "next-ticket"}}, {{skillRef "describe-ticket"}}, {{skillRef "execute-ticket"}}, {{skillRef "review-ticket"}}, {{skillRef "merge-ticket"}} — the slash command runs the same procedure.

## Where the state lives

All shared state — user stories, the plan (as checkboxes), the PR link, and the review verdict — lives in a single comment **on the ticket itself** (the "work artifact"). It's updated in place, so the workflow resumes seamlessly across sessions, machines, and even a different one of the supported tools. Nothing important lives in untracked local files.

## One-time setup for contributors

To use these skills you need:

1. **The {{backend.displayName}} MCP server** — its config is already scaffolded for the tools this repo uses (e.g. `.mcp.json` for Claude Code), so on first launch you just **approve the server and complete the {{backend.displayName}} sign-in** when prompted. (Under the hood: {{backend.requires}})
2. **The `gh` CLI authenticated** — run `gh auth login` against this repo's GitHub remote (used by execute / review / merge).

## First run

Open this repo in your AI assistant and ask: **"what should I work on next?"** — that runs `next-ticket` and recommends where to start.

